Description: VersusLaw is a recognized leader in electronic distribution of legal research materials.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Minneapolis-Saint Paul Area, Great Lakes, Midwestern US
Full Description: VersusLaw's focus was originally to provide the legal community with accurate, current, and in-depth information exclusively on one topic - professional liability. The Company created a monthly journal on legal ethics titled Lawyers Liability Review (LLR) and published the first issue in February 1986.  In the early 1990s, Timeline began the electronic collection and distribution of court opinions and other primary research materials. Timeline was an early adopter of the World Wide Web and in August 1995 was among the first web-based legal content providers, carrying opinions from the U.S. Supreme Court, the Federal Circuit Courts of Appeals, and State appellate courts. Reflecting a new direction and the company's commitment to electronic distribution of legal research materials, in 1996, Timeline Publishing changed its name to VersusLaw, Inc., and launched a new web site devoted exclusively to the distribution of primary materials to the legal profession.  Today, VersusLaw continues to broaden its focus and mission: to provide all legal practitioners access to current, in-depth, easy-to-use legal research, regardless of the size of their firms, by using the power of technology. The company has a deep-seated belief that knowledge is power and that this power should be available to everyone quickly, easily and affordably.

So join us and put aside the cares of the week and find yourself in the presence of case managers, who really care about helping you. Description: Elevating brands with actionable analytics to grow sales.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Denver Area, Western US
Full Description: We're well into the 21st century and consumer packaged goods (CPG) brands of all sizes in the $1T+ USA grocery segment still don't know where their products are sold (in-store or online), let alone understand the value generated by their own marketing activities. Even when they possess the data, brands lack the time, skills, and tools to identify and act upon insights that enable them to grow sales and operate efficiently. Current 3rd Party analytics providers are siloed by sales channel, expensive, and often no more than data collection entities, thus home-grown analytics solutions that yield limited insights have remained the dominant solution across the industry. Snowrise's vision, Analytics For All, reflects our belief that all brands can benefit from analytics services that address a plethora of common challenges, similar to what materialized for bookkeeping and taxes decades ago. Our philosophy is that successful services need to be, in priority order, Actionable, Affordable, and Advanced. The lack of AI is not the reason emerging and mature brands don't know where their products are sold today, it is because existing solutions are not actionable. And while Snowrise is a strong believer in the value of Advanced analytics solutions, we understand that the fundamentals need to be in place if that value is to be realized. Snowrise performs the analytics for brands so they can quickly discover, share, and act to grow sales. We support all sales channels (ex. grocery, ecommerce, specialty) and can combine each brand's unique criteria (ex. planograms) with any data set to get actionable insights to the right team members. Our five revenue-generating analytics services, two of which were launched in 3Q22, elevate sales team performance, quantify marketing campaigns, and provide consolidated insights across all sales channels.
Industry Groups: Artificial Intelligence (AI), Commerce and Shopping, Data and Analytics, Hardware, Other, Science and Engineering, Software

Headquarters Regions: Greater Atlanta Area, East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: Center for Civic Innovation hosts programs for community-based social entrepreneurs at all stages but they focus their investments on early stage, untested projects. The Center for Civic Innovation helps the public sector find and invest in more innovative or effective ways to tackle local social challenges. The Center’s main program, Civic Labs, facilitates pay-for-outcome contracts between local public agencies (a local government, nonprofit, or foundation) and entrepreneurs with solutions that save money, generate revenue, and engage local communities. The Center’s innovation lab offers public sector organizations and local civic innovators a safe space for experimenting and prototyping untested, promising civic ideas. They also offer trainings, workshops, and opportunities for constructive dialogue. The Center is grateful for the support of a number of local and national advisors, including Bill Bolling of the Atlanta Community Food Bank, Sonal Shah, of the Georgetown Beeck Center for Social Impact and Innovation, and Brian McGowan of the Metro Atlanta Chamber.

Today, as they continue to grow throughout central Indiana, their focus is always on providing the highest level of customer service, maintaining deep company relationships, and consistently going beyond the call of duty. They have developed long-standing ties with their carriers over the years and have gained the trust of their customers and community by keeping the business locally owned and operated.The IMG mission is to be the very best in their field of insurance and risk management. They strive to provide their clients with an authentic experience by making sure they know the types of coverage available to them, as well as their unique risks. By identifying those risks, and teaching their clients how to reduce or eliminate them, we are not just writing insurance policies — they are empowering their clients to take control of the factors in their lives or businesses that could result in a claim. It’s impossible to predict the future (which is why insurance is so important), but proper risk management techniques have been proven to make a big difference in their clients’ lives.
